<section xml:id="sec_sum_conj">
  <title>Conjectures of Explicit Formulas for Sums and Products</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Although we have a notation for sums and products,
      we still need to go through a process to evaluate a sum and product.
      First, we need to calculate each term.
      Next, we need to add or multiply.
      In some cases,
      we can find an explicit formula for a sum or a product,
      which allows us to evaluate using a formula.
      In this section,
      we introduce partial sums and partial products and use them to conjecture explicit formulas.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_sum_conj">
    <title>\subsumconj</title>
    <p>
      We start with sums.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_partial_sum">
      <title>Partial sums</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider a list of numbers
          <m>a_s, a_{s+1}, a_{s+2}, \ldots,
          a_n</m> for some integers <m>s</m> and <m>n</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For the sum
                <me>
                  \sum_{k=s}^n a_k =a_s + a_{s+1}+a_{s+2}+\ldots+a_n
                </me>,
                the <term>partial sums</term> are
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sum_{k=s}^s a_k \amp  =a_s,</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sum_{k=s}^{s+1} a_k \amp  =a_s+a_{s+1},</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sum_{k=s}^{s+2} a_k \amp  =a_s+a_{s+1}+a_{s+2}</mrow>
                </md>,
                and so on.
                For example, for the sum
                <me>
                  \sum_{k=1}^n 2 =2 + 2 + 2 + \ldots + 2
                </me>,
                the partial sums are
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^1 2 \amp =2,</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^2 2 \amp =2+2=4,</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^3 2 \amp =2+2+2=6</mrow>
                </md>,
                and so on.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The <term>sequence of partial sums</term> is
                <me>
                  a_s, a_s+a_{s+1},a_s+a_{s+1}+a_{s+2}, \ldots
                </me>.
                For example, the sequence of partial sums in our example begins
                <me>
                  2, 4, 6, \ldots
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      We focus on finite sums,
      but we mention, for readers who have studied calculus,
      that these are the same partial sums used to define infinite series.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is a shorthand notation for calculating partial sums that we introduce in our next example,
      where we revisit the sum from <xref ref="defn_partial_sum"></xref>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_partial_sums_conj_constant">
      <title>Conjecture explicit form of sum of constant</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the sum
          <me>
            \sum_{k=1}^n 2 =2 + 2 + 2 + \ldots + 2
          </me>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate the partial sums.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We display the partial sums using a shorthand in <xref ref="fig_part_sums_constant"></xref>.
                    At each <m>+</m> sign,
                    we draw a line and record the sum from the beginning to that line.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig_part_sums_constant">
                  <caption>Calculating partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n2</m>.</caption>
                  image type not recognized
                </figure>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Display the partial sums in a table.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We are interested in finding an explicit formula sum as a function of <m>n</m>,
                    so it is helpful to have the partial sums in a table,
                    as shown in <xref ref="tab_partial_sums_constant"></xref>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="tab_partial_sums_constant">
                  <title>Partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n2</m></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>n</m></cell>
                      <cell>1</cell>
                      <cell>2</cell>
                      <cell>3</cell>
                      <cell>4</cell>
                      <cell>5</cell>
                      <cell>6</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>partial sum</cell>
                      <cell>2</cell>
                      <cell>4</cell>
                      <cell>6</cell>
                      <cell>8</cell>
                      <cell>10</cell>
                      <cell>12</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>pattern</cell>
                      <cell>2(1)</cell>
                      <cell>2(2)</cell>
                      <cell>2(3)</cell>
                      <cell>2(4)</cell>
                      <cell>2(5)</cell>
                      <cell>2(6)</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit form.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We notice that each partial sum is twice the index <m>n</m>,
                    and add another row to our table to show the pattern.
                    We conjecture <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n2=2n</m>,
                    which is no surprise since
                    <me>
                      \sum_{k=1}^n2 = \underbrace{2 +2+ \ldots + 2}_{n \text{ times } }=2n
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Observe that we can use each partial sum to calculate the next partial sum without having to add from the beginning.
      For example,
      once we calculate <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^32 = 2+2+2 = 6</m>,
      we can calculate
      <me>
        \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^42 = 2+2+2+2 = (2+2+2)+2=6+2=8
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is, the new partial sum is equal to the previous partial sum plus the new term.
      We state this result in general.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_rec_def_partial_sum">
      <title>Recursive definition of partial sums</title>
      <p>
        Consider a list of numbers
        <m>a_s, a_{s+1}, a_{s+2}, \ldots,
        a_n</m> for some integers <m>s</m> and <m>n</m>.
        Then
        <md>
          <mrow>\sum_{k=s}^n a_k \amp  = a_s + a_{s+1} + \ldots + a_{n-1} + a_n</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp  = (a_s + a_{s+1} + \ldots + a_{n-1}) + a_n</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp  = \left(\sum_{k=s}^{n-1} a_k\right) + a_n</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        We can remember this recursion as
        <me>
          \underbrace{\sum_{k=s}^n a_k}_{\text{ new sum } } = \underbrace{\sum_{k=s}^{n-1} a_k}_{\text{ previous sum } } + \underbrace{a_n}_{\text{ new term } }
        </me>
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Let's look at a couple more examples of calculating partial sums and using pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_conj_explicit_sum_linear_exp">
      <title>Conjecture explicit formula for sum</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the first few partial sums,
          display your findings in a table,
          and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(4k-1)</m>    Hint: Factor.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We start by writing out the first six terms and their partial sums,
                    as shown in <xref ref="fig_part_sums_linear"></xref>.
                    For example, <m>3+7 = 10</m>.
                    Next, using the previous sum
                    (as in <xref ref="rem_rec_def_partial_sum"></xref>)
                    we get <m>3+7+11 = (10) + 11 = 21</m>.
                    Then, <m>21 + 15 = 36</m>, and so on.
                    Next, we make a table showing the index <m>n</m> and the partial sums,
                    as shown in <xref ref="tab_partial_sums_linear"></xref>.
                    To see the pattern, we follow the hint and factor each partial sum.
                    We show this pattern in the third row of the table.
                    Notice that one factor is <m>n</m> itself.
                    The other factor is odd.
                    Based on this pattern, we conjecture that
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(4k-1)=n(2n+1)
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig_part_sums_linear">
                  <caption>Calculating partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(4k-1)</m>.</caption>
                  image type not recognized
                </figure>
                <table xml:id="tab_partial_sums_linear">
                  <title>Partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(4k-1)</m></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>n</m></cell>
                      <cell>1</cell>
                      <cell>2</cell>
                      <cell>3</cell>
                      <cell>4</cell>
                      <cell>5</cell>
                      <cell>6</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>partial sum</cell>
                      <cell>3</cell>
                      <cell>10</cell>
                      <cell>21</cell>
                      <cell>36</cell>
                      <cell>55</cell>
                      <cell>78</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>pattern</cell>
                      <cell>1(3)</cell>
                      <cell>2(5)</cell>
                      <cell>3(7)</cell>
                      <cell>4(9)</cell>
                      <cell>5(11)</cell>
                      <cell>6(13)</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n9 \cdot 10^k</m>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We start by writing out the first four terms and their partial sums,
                    as shown in <xref ref="fig_part_sums_geometric"></xref>.
                    For example, <xref ref="rem_rec_def_partial_sum">using</xref>,
                    we calculate <m>9+90=99</m>, then <m>99 + 900 = 999</m>,
                    and so on.
                    Next, we make a table showing the index <m>n</m> and the partial sums,
                    as shown in <xref ref="tab_partial_sums_geometric"></xref>.
                    We notice that the partial sums are related to powers of 10 and,
                    in fact, they are each one less than the next higher power of 10.
                    We show this pattern in the third row of the table.
                    Based on this pattern, we conjecture that
                    <me>
                      \displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n9 \cdot 10^k=10^{n+1}-1
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig_part_sums_geometric">
                  <caption>Calculating partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n9 \cdot 10^k</m>.</caption>
                  image type not recognized
                </figure>
                <table xml:id="tab_partial_sums_geometric">
                  <title>Partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n9 \cdot 10^k</m></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>n</m></cell>
                      <cell>1</cell>
                      <cell>2</cell>
                      <cell>3</cell>
                      <cell>4</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>partial sum</cell>
                      <cell>9</cell>
                      <cell>99</cell>
                      <cell>999</cell>
                      <cell>9999</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>pattern</cell>
                      <cell><m>10^1-1</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>10^2-1</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>10^3-1</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>10^4-1</m></cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      It is your turn to conjecture explicit forms of a sum.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_sum_conj">
      <title>Sum conjectures</title>
      <p>
        For each problem,
        calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to complete a conjecture about an explicit formula for the sum.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n2^k = 1+2+4+\ldots +2^n</m> Hint: The answer involves powers of two.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(2k)=2+4+6+ \ldots + 2n</m> Hint: Factor.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_sum_recip_hs">
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n\frac{2}{k(k+1)}= 1 + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{6} + \ldots+\frac{2}{n(n+1)}</m> Use computational technology to find the partial sums as fractions.
              (In DESMOS, click the fraction icon to ask for the answer as a fraction.)
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Let's look <xref ref="act_sum_conj">at</xref>
      <xref ref="part_sum_recip_hs"/>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_sum_recip_hs_conj">
      <title>Explicit form of sum of reciprocals of handshake numbers</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to complete a conjecture about an explicit formula for the sum
          <me>
            \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n\frac{2}{k(k+1)}= 1 + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{6} + \ldots+\frac{2}{n(n+1)}
          </me>
        </p>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The first five partial sums are
            <me>
              1, \frac{4}{3}, \frac{3}{2}, \frac{8}{5}, \frac{5}{3}, \frac{12}{7}
            </me>.
            Notice the denominators are of the form
            <me>
              \underline{\hspace{.2in}}, 3, \underline{\hspace{.2in}}, 5, \underline{\hspace{.2in}}, 7
            </me>
            which suggests that we should rewrite the fractions over the denominators
            <me>
              2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7
            </me>
            to get
            <me>
              \frac{2}{2}, \frac{4}{3}, \frac{6}{4}, \frac{8}{5}, \frac{10}{6}, \frac{12}{7}
            </me>.
            Next, we make a table showing the index <m>n</m> and the partial sums,
            as shown in <xref ref="tab_partial_sums_recip_hs"></xref>.
            Based on this pattern, we conjecture that
            <me>
              \sum_{k=1}^n\frac{2}{k(k+1)}= \frac{2n}{n+1}
            </me>
          </p>
        </solution>
        <table xml:id="tab_partial_sums_recip_hs">
          <title>Partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n\frac{2}{k(k+1)}</m></title>
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><m>n</m></cell>
              <cell>1</cell>
              <cell>2</cell>
              <cell>3</cell>
              <cell>4</cell>
              <cell>5</cell>
              <cell>6</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>partial sum</cell>
              <cell>1</cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle \frac{4}{3}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{3}{2}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{8}{5}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{5}{3}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{12}{7}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>pattern</cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{2}{2}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{4}{3}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{6}{4}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{8}{5}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{10}{6}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\displaystyle\frac{12}{7}</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_prod_conj">
    <title>\subprodconj</title>
    <p>
      Next, we work with products.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_partial_prod">
      <title>Partial products</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider a list of numbers
          <m>a_s, a_{s+1}, a_{s+2}, \ldots,
          a_n</m> for some integers <m>s</m> and <m>n</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For the product
                <me>
                  \prod_{k=s}^n a_k =a_s \times a_{s+1} \times a_{s+2} \times \ldots \times a_n
                </me>,
                the <term>partial products</term> are
                <md>
                  <mrow>\prod_{k=s}^s a_k \amp =a_s,</mrow>
                  <mrow>\prod_{k=s}^{s+1} a_k \amp =a_s \times a_{s+1},</mrow>
                  <mrow>\prod_{k=s}^{s+2} a_k \amp =a_s \times a_{s+1} \times a_{s+2}</mrow>
                </md>,
                and so on.
                For example, for the product
                <me>
                  \prod_{k=1}^n 2 = 2 \times 2 \times \cdots \times 2
                </me>,
                the partial products are
                <md>
                  <mrow>\prod_{k=1}^1 2 \amp =2,</mrow>
                  <mrow>\prod_{k=1}^2 2 \amp =2 \times 2=4,</mrow>
                  <mrow>\prod_{k=1}^3 2 \amp =2 \times 2 \times 2=8</mrow>
                </md>,
                and so on.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The <term>sequence of partial products</term> is
                <me>
                  a_s, a_sa_{s+1},a_sa_{s+1}a_{s+2}, \ldots
                </me>.
                For example,
                the sequence of partial products in our example begins
                <me>
                  2, 4, 8, \ldots
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      There is a shorthand notation for calculating partial products that we introduce in our next example,
      where we revisit the product from <xref ref="defn_partial_prod"></xref>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_partial_prod_conj_constant">
      <title>Conjecture explicit form of product of constant</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the product
          <me>
            \prod_{k=1}^n 2 =2 \times 2 \times 2 \times \ldots \times 2
          </me>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Calculate the partial products.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We display the partial products using a shorthand in <xref ref="fig_part_products_constant"></xref>.
                    At each <times/> sign,
                    we draw a line and record the product from the beginning to that line.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <figure xml:id="fig_part_products_constant">
                  <caption>Calculating partial products for <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n2</m>.</caption>
                  image type not recognized
                </figure>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Display the partial products in a table.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We are interested in finding an explicit formula for the product as a function of <m>n</m>,
                    so it is helpful to have the partial products in a table,
                    as shown in <xref ref="tab_partial_products_constant"></xref>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
                <table xml:id="tab_partial_products_constant">
                  <title>Partial products for <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n2</m></title>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>n</m></cell>
                      <cell>1</cell>
                      <cell>2</cell>
                      <cell>3</cell>
                      <cell>4</cell>
                      <cell>5</cell>
                      <cell>6</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>partial product</cell>
                      <cell>2</cell>
                      <cell>4</cell>
                      <cell>8</cell>
                      <cell>16</cell>
                      <cell>32</cell>
                      <cell>64</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row bottom="minor">
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell>pattern</cell>
                      <cell><m>2^1</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>2^2</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>2^3</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>2^4</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>2^5</m></cell>
                      <cell><m>2^6</m></cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit form.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We notice that each partial product is two to the index <m>n</m>,
                    and add another row to our table to show the pattern.
                    We conjecture <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n2=2^n</m>,
                    which is no surprise since
                    <me>
                      \prod_{k=1}^n2 = \underbrace{2 \times 2 \times \ldots \times 2}_{n \text{ times } }=2^n
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Observe that we can use each partial product to calculate the next partial product without having to multiply from the beginning.
      For example,
      once we calculate <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^32 = 2 \times 2 \times 2 = 8</m>,
      we can calculate
      <me>
        \displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^42 = 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2 = (2 \times 2 \times 2)\times 2=8 \times 2=16
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is, the new partial product is equal to the previous partial product times the new term.
      We state this result in general.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_rec_def_partial_prod">
      <title>Recursive definition of partial product</title>
      <p>
        Consider a list of numbers
        <m>a_s, a_{s+1}, a_{s+2}, \ldots,
        a_n</m> for some integers <m>s</m> and <m>n</m>.
        Then
        <md>
          <mrow>\prod_{k=s}^n a_k \amp  = a_s \times a_{s+1} \times \ldots \times a_{n-1} \times a_n</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp  = (a_s \times a_{s+1}\times \ldots \times a_{n-1}) \times a_n</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp  = \left(\prod_{k=s}^{n-1} a_k\right) \times  a_n</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        We can remember this recursion as
        <me>
          \underbrace{\prod_{k=s}^n a_k}_{\text{ new product } } = \underbrace{\prod_{k=s}^{n-1} a_k}_{\text{ previous product } } \times \underbrace{a_n}_{\text{ new term } }
        </me>
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Let's look at another example of calculating partial products and using pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_conj_explicit_prod_linear">
      <title>Conjecture explicit formula for product</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the first few partial products,
          display your findings in a table,
          and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the product:
          <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^nk</m>.
        </p>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We start by writing out the first six terms and their partial products,
            as shown in <xref ref="fig_part_product_linear"></xref>.
            For example, <m>1 \times 2 = 2</m>.
            Next, using the previous product
            (as in <xref ref="rem_rec_def_partial_prod"></xref>)
            we get <m>1 \times 2 \times 3 = (2) \times 3 = 6</m>.
            Then, <m>6 \times 4 = 24</m>, and so on.
            Next, we make a table showing the index <m>n</m> and the partial products,
            as shown in <xref ref="tab_partial_products_linear"></xref>.
            We recognize these numbers as the factorials
            (or we realize that we are multiplying consecutive integers).
            We show this pattern in the third row of the table.
            Based on this pattern,
            we conjecture that <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^nk=n!</m>,
            which is no surprise because <m>1 \times 2 \times 3 \times \cdots \times n = n!</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
        <figure xml:id="fig_part_product_linear">
          <caption>Calculating partial products for <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^nk</m>.</caption>
          image type not recognized
        </figure>
        <table xml:id="tab_partial_products_linear">
          <title>Partial products for <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^nk</m></title>
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><m>n</m></cell>
              <cell>1</cell>
              <cell>2</cell>
              <cell>3</cell>
              <cell>4</cell>
              <cell>5</cell>
              <cell>6</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>partial product</cell>
              <cell>1</cell>
              <cell>2</cell>
              <cell>6</cell>
              <cell>24</cell>
              <cell>120</cell>
              <cell>720</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>pattern</cell>
              <cell><m>1!</m></cell>
              <cell><m>2!</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3!</m></cell>
              <cell><m>4!</m></cell>
              <cell><m>5!</m></cell>
              <cell><m>6!</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      It is your turn to conjecture explicit forms of a product.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_prod_conj">
      <title>Product conjectures</title>
      <p>
        For each problem,
        calculate the first few partial products and use pattern recognition to complete a conjecture about an explicit formula for the product.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \prod_{j=1}^n \frac{j+1}{j} = \frac{2}{1} \times \frac{3}{2} \times \frac{4}{3} \times \cdots \times \frac{n+1}{n}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n(2k) = 2(1) \times 2(2) \times 2(3) \times \cdots \times 2(n)</m>.
              Hint: Keep the partial products factored.
              Group together the twos to write one factor as a power of two.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_sum_fib">
    <title>\subsumfib</title>
    <p>
      There are some interesting identities involving sums of Fibonacci numbers.
      Try an example.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_fib_sums_conj">
      <title>Fibonacci sums conjectures</title>
      <p>
        Recall that the Fibonacci numbers are defined by <m>F_0=0</m>,
        <m>F_1=1</m>,
        and <m>F_n = F_{n-1}+F_{n-2}</m> for <m>n \ge 2</m>.
        The first few Fibonacci numbers are listed in <xref ref="tab_15fibs"></xref>.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="tab_15fibs">
        <title>The first fifteen Fibonacci numbers</title>
        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell><m>F_0=0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_1=1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_2=1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_3=2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_4=3</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>F_5=5</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_6=8</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_7=13</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_8=21</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_9=34</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>F_{10}=55</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_{11}=89</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_{12} = 144</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_{13} = 233</m></cell>
            <cell><m>F_{14} = 377</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <ol>
        <li xml:id="part_fib_sums_even_index">
          <p>
            Calculate the first six partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <md>
              <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^nF_{2k} \amp  = F_2+F_4+F_6+F_8+F_{10}+F_{12}+\ldots +F_{2n}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp  = 1+3+8+21+55+144+ \ldots +F_{2n}</mrow>
            </md>
            Hint: Add one to each partial sum to see the pattern.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="part_Fib_sums_alt_act">
          <p>
            Calculate the first six partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <md>
              <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^n(-1)^{k+1}F_k \amp  = F_1-F_2+F_3-F_4+F_5-F_6+ \ldots +(-1)^{n+1}F_n</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp  = 1-1+2-3+5-8+ \ldots +F_{2n}</mrow>
            </md>
            Hint: Subtract one from each partial sum to see the pattern.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Let's take a closer look at the sum from <xref ref="act_fib_sums_conj"></xref>
      <xref ref="part_fib_sums_even_index"/>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_fib_sum_conj_even_index">
      <title>Fibonacci sum conjecture</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the first six partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
          <md>
            <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^nF_{2k} \amp  = F_2+F_4+F_6+F_8+F_{10}+F_{12}+ \ldots +F_{2n}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp  = 1+3+8+21+55+144 \ldots +F_{2n}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          The first fifteen Fibonacci numbers appear in <xref ref="tab_15fibs"></xref>.
        </p>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We start by writing out the first six terms and their partial sums,
            as shown in <xref ref="fig_part_sums_fib"></xref>.
            For example, <m>1+3 = 4</m>.
            Next, using the previous sum
            (as in <xref ref="rem_rec_def_partial_sum"></xref>)
            we get <m>1+3+8 = (4) + 8 = 12</m>.
            Then, <m>12 + 21 = 33</m>, and so on.
            Next, we make a table showing the index <m>n</m> and the partial sums,
            as shown in <xref ref="tab_partial_sums_fib"></xref>.
            To see the pattern,
            notice that each partial sum is one less than a Fibonacci number.
            Notice that the subscripts are odd.
            We conjecture
            <me>
              \sum_{k=1}^nF_{2k}=F_{2n+1}-1
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
        <figure xml:id="fig_part_sums_fib">
          <caption>Calculating partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nF_{2k}</m>.</caption>
          image type not recognized
        </figure>
        <table xml:id="tab_partial_sums_fib">
          <title>Partial sums for <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^nF_{2k}</m></title>
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><m>n</m></cell>
              <cell>1</cell>
              <cell>2</cell>
              <cell>3</cell>
              <cell>4</cell>
              <cell>5</cell>
              <cell>6</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>partial sum</cell>
              <cell>1</cell>
              <cell>4</cell>
              <cell>12</cell>
              <cell>33</cell>
              <cell>88</cell>
              <cell>232</cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>pattern</cell>
              <cell><m>2-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>5-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>13-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>34-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>89-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>233-1</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>=</m></cell>
              <cell><m>F_3-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>F_5-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>F_7-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>F_9-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>F_{11}-1</m></cell>
              <cell><m>F_{13}-1</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_factor_polys">
    <title>\subfactorpolys</title>
    <p>
      In some of our conjectures about sums and products,
      our answer involved a factored polynomial.
      We would like to eventually prove these conjectures.
      For those proofs, it is helpful to be able to factor polynomials.
      As we saw in <xref ref="sub_polys"></xref>,
      we use the distributive rule to multiply polynomials.
      Let's look at an example using the distributive rule to factor polynomials.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_unfoil">
      <title>Factoring polynomial</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li xml:id="part_expand_binomial_general">
              <p>
                Multiply <m>(n+s)(n+t)</m> and write the answer as a polynomial in the variable <m>n</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Using the distributive property (FOIL) as discussed in <xref ref="sub_polys"></xref>, we get
                  </p>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>(n+s)(n+t)</m></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>\underbrace{(n)(n)}_{\text{ First } } +\underbrace{(n)(t)}_{\text{ Outside } } + \underbrace{(s)(n)}_{\text{ Inside } } + \underbrace{(s)(t)}_{\text{ Last } }</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>n^2 + tn + sn + st</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>n^2+ (s+t)n + st</m></cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                  <p>
                    Observe that the coefficient <m>n</m> is <m>s+t</m>,
                    the sum of <m>s</m> and <m>t</m>,
                    and the constant term is <m>st</m>,
                    the product of <m>s</m> and <m>t</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Factor <m>n^2 -n-6</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Based on our observation in <xref ref="part_expand_binomial_general"/>, we might guess that
                    <me>
                      n^2 -n-6 = (n+\underline{})(n+\underline{})
                    </me>
                    where the sum of the integers in the blanks is <m>-1</m> and the product of the integers in the blanks is <m>-6</m>.
                    We guess that the integers are <m>-3</m> and <m>2</m> and so
                    <me>
                      \text{ answer: } n^2 -n-6 = (n-3)(n+2)
                    </me>.
                    This process of factoring is sometimes nicknamed
                    <term>unfoiling</term>, since we FOIL to check.
                    <me>
                      \text{ check: } (n-3)(n+2)=n^2 + 2n-3n-6 = n^2-n-6
                    </me>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_diff_sq">
              <p>
                Multiply <m>(n+s)(n-s)</m> and write the answer as a polynomial in the variable <m>n</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Multiplying we get
                  </p>
                  <tabular>
                    <row>
                      <cell><m>(n+s)(n-s)</m></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>\underbrace{(n)(n)}_{\text{ First } } +\underbrace{(n)(-s)}_{\text{ Outside } } + \underbrace{(s)(n)}_{\text{ Inside } } + \underbrace{(s)(-s)}_{\text{ Last } }</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>n^2 - sn + sn - s^2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                      <cell></cell>
                      <cell>=</cell>
                      <cell><m>n^2-s^2</m></cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Factor <m>n^2 -4</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We can use the result of <xref ref="part_diff_sq"/>,
                    <me>
                      n^2-4 = n^2-2^2=(n+2)(n-2)
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Practice using the FOIL method to factor polynomials.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_UNFOIL">
      <title>Factoring olynomials</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Factor <m>m^2+3m+2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Factor <m>m^2-1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Factor <m>2k^2+3k+1</m>.
              Hint: Try a product of the form <m>(2k + \underline{})(k+\underline{})</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Let's look at another example.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_factor_nonmonic_quad">
      <title>Factor quadratic polynomial</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor <m>3k^2+2k-1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let's try a product of the form <m>(3k + \underline{})(k+\underline{})</m>.
          To get the constant term <m>-1</m>,
          one of the blanks must be 1 and the other must be <m>-1</m>.
          Since
          <me>
            (3k -1)(k+1)=3k^2+3k-k-1=3k^2+2k-1
          </me>,
          we can factor <m>3k^2+2k-1 = (3k -1)(k+1)</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_sum_conj">for</xref> \subsumconj</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_partial_sums">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first five partial sums for each sum.
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_partial_sum_powers3">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n2 \cdot 3^k</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_partial_sums_constant">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{n}3</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_partial_sums_alt">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \sum_{m=0}^{n}(-1)^m</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_partial_sums_square">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \sum_{j=1}^{n}(6j^2)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_powers3_constant">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the partial sums from <xref ref="exer_partial_sums"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_partial_sum_powers3"/> to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n2 \cdot 3^k</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the partial sums from <xref ref="exer_partial_sums"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_partial_sums_constant"/> to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{i=1}^{n}3</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_odds">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(2k-1)
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_alt_sum_sq">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the partial sums from <xref ref="exer_partial_sums"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_partial_sums_alt"/> to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{m=0}^{n}(-1)^m</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the partial sums from <xref ref="exer_partial_sums"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_partial_sums_square"/> to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{j=0}^{n}(6j^2)</m>.
                  Hint: Factor.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_factorials">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \sum_{k=1}^nk(k!)
            </me>.
            By the way, the result of this exercise is a key step in proving the uniqueness of the factorial representations introduced in <xref ref="act_fact_rep"></xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_recip_powers2">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n\frac{1}{2^k}
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_new_odds">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n(2k+3)
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_powers5">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n 4 \cdot 5^k</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_4kplus1">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n(4k+1)
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_alt_sq">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \sum_{k=1}^n(-1)^kk^2
            </me>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_4kminus3">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \displaystyle \sum_{k=0}^n(4k-3)
            </me>.
            Hint: Factor.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_fraction">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n\frac{1}{(2k-1)(2k+1)}
            </me>.
            Note that DESMOS adds fractions exactly if you click on the fraction icon.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_sum_conj">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to calculate a partial sum?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why it is useful to have a recursive definition of a partial sum?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use partial sums and pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for a sum?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_cubes">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum
            <me>
              \displaystyle \sum_{m=1}^n6m^3
            </me>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Hint: Factor.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_conj_alt_sum">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial sums and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the sum <m>\displaystyle \sum_{k=1}^n(-1)^kk</m>.
            Hint: The formula involves the ceiling.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_prod_conj">for</xref> \subprodconj</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_partial_prod">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first five partial products for each product.
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_partial_prod_recip">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n\frac{1}{k}</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_partial_prod_3">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \prod_{i=1}^n3</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_partial_prod_3k">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n3k</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_partial_prod_square">
                <p>
                  <m>\displaystyle \prod_{j=1}^nj^2</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prod_conj_recip_constant">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the partial products from <xref ref="exer_partial_prod"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_partial_prod_recip"/> to conjecture an explicit formula for the product <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n\frac{1}{k}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the partial products from <xref ref="exer_partial_prod"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_partial_prod_3"/> to conjecture an explicit formula for the product <m>\displaystyle \prod_{i=1}^n3</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prod_conj_3k_square">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the partial products from <xref ref="exer_partial_prod"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_partial_prod_3k"/> to conjecture an explicit formula for the product <m>\displaystyle \prod_{k=1}^n3k</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the partial products from <xref ref="exer_partial_prod"></xref>
                  <xref ref="part_partial_prod_square"/> to conjecture an explicit formula for the product <m>\displaystyle \prod_{j=1}^nj^2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prod_conj_1minus1overj">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial products and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the product
            <me>
              \displaystyle \prod_{j=2}^n \left(1 - \frac{1}{j}\right)
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prod_conj_twice_sq">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial products and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the product <m>\displaystyle \prod_{j=1}^n(2j^2)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prod_conj_2overj">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first few partial products and use pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for the product <m>\displaystyle \prod_{j=1}^n \frac{2}{j}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_product_conj">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to calculate a partial product?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why it is useful to have a recursive definition of a partial product?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use partial products and pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for a product?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_sum_fib">for</xref> \subsumfib</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_firstn_Fib_conj">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first six partial sums and conjecture an explicit form for the sum
            <md>
              <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^nF_k \amp  = F_1+F_2+F_3+F_4+F_5+ + \ldots +F_n</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp  =1 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 5 +\ldots + F_n</mrow>
            </md>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_sum_firstn_Fib_sq_conj">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first six partial sums and conjecture an explicit form for the sum
            <md>
              <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^n(F_k)^2 \amp  = F_1^2+F_2^2+F_3^2+F_4^2+F_5^2+\ldots+F_n^2</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp  = 1^2+1^2+2^2+3^2+5^2+\ldots + F_n^2</mrow>
            </md>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_fib_sum_odd_terms_conj">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Calculate the first six partial sums and conjecture an explicit form for the sum
            <md>
              <mrow>\sum_{k=1}^{n}F_{2k-1} \amp  = F_1+F_3 +F_5 +F_7+F_9+ \ldots + F_{2n-1}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp  = 1+2+5+13+34+\ldots + F_{2n-1}</mrow>
            </md>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_fib_sums">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to calculate a partial sum that involves Fibonacci numbers?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use partial sums and pattern recognition to conjecture an explicit formula for a sum involving Fibonacci numbers?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_factor_polys">for</xref> \subfactorpolys</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_factor_quad_poly">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Factor <m>n^2-n-2</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Factor <m>n^2+5n+4</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Factor <m>n^2+5n-6</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Factor <m>n^2-9</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_simplify_factor">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Expand each expression, simplify,
            then factor the answer as much as possible.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(n-1)n + 2n</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>n(2n-1)+(4n+1)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(n-1)n(2n-1) + 6n^2</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_factor_polys">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What is means to factor a polynomial?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to factor a quadratic polynomial?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to factor the difference of squares?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Select Answers and Hints</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_partial_sums"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>2, 8, 26, \ldots</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>3, 6, 9, \ldots</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>1, 0, 1, \ldots</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>6, 30, 84, \ldots</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_conj_powers3_constant"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer involves a power of three,
            but not exactly <m>3^n</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer is a multiple of 3.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_conj_odds"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The partial sums are <m>1, 4, 9, \ldots</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_conj_alt_sum_sq"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Use <m>(-1)^n</m> to get a closed formula,
            noting that <m>\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{2} =1</m> and <m>\frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{2} =0</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>6 = (1)(2)(3)</m> and <m>30 = (2)(3)(5)</m>.
            The first factor equals <m>n</m>,
            what are the next two factors, in terms of <m>n</m>?
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_conj_factorials"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The partial sums begin
        <m>1, 5, 23, \ldots</m> and the formula involves factorials,
        but not exactly <m>n!</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_conj_recip_powers2"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The partial sums are <m>1, \frac{3}{2}, \frac{7}{4}, \ldots</m>.
        One version of the formula is a fraction in which the numerator involves a power of two
        (but not exactly <m>2^n</m>)
        and the denominator is <m>2^n</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_conj_4kplus1"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Factor the partial sums.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_conj_powers5"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The formula involves powers of five,
        but not exactly <m>5^n</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_conj_4kplus1"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Factor the partial sums.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_partial_prod"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>\displaystyle 1, \frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{6}, \ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>3, 9, 27, \ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>3, 18, 162, \ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: <m>1, 4, 36, \ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prod_conj_recip_constant"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer involves factorial.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: The answer involves a power of three.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prod_conj_3k_square"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Keep the partial products factored:
            <m>(3 \cdot 1), (3 \cdot 1)(3 \cdot 2),(3 \cdot 1)(3 \cdot 2)(3 \cdot 3)</m>, Then collect the threes.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Keep the partial products factored:
            <m>(1 \cdot 1),(1 \cdot 1)(2 \cdot 2), (1 \cdot 1)(2 \cdot 2)(3 \cdot 3)</m>.
            The answer involves factorials.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prod_conj_1minus1overj"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: <m>1 - \frac{1}{2} = \frac{1}{2}</m>,
        <m>1 - \frac{1}{3} = \frac{2}{3}</m>,
        <m>1 - \frac{1}{4} = \frac{3}{4}</m>,
        so our product is <m>\frac{1}{2}\cdot \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{3}{4} \cdots</m> and,
        therefore,
        the partial product are <m>\frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{4}, \ldots</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prod_conj_twice_sq"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Keep the partial products factored:
        <m>(2\cdot 1 \cdot 1),(2\cdot 1 \cdot 1)(2\cdot 2 \cdot 2),(2\cdot 1 \cdot 1)(2\cdot 2 \cdot 2)(2\cdot 3 \cdot 3) , \ldots</m>.
        Then collect twos.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_prod_conj_2overj"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Keep the numerator and denominator factored and do not reduce the fractions.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_firstn_Fib_conj"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The formula involves Fibonacci numbers.
        For example, <m>12 = 13-1 = F_7-1</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_sum_firstn_Fib_sq_conj"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The formula involves Fibonacci numbers.
        Another hint: Factor.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_fib_sum_odd_terms_conj"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: the answers involved Fibonacci numbers.
        For example, <m>55 = F_{10}</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>